SIMPLE: univocal
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Univocal
<hw>U*niv"o*cal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>univocus</ets>; <ets>unus</ets> one + <ets>vox</ets>,
<ets>vocis</ets>, a voice, word. See <er>One</er>, and
<er>Voice</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Having one meaning only; --
contrasted with <ant>equivocal</ant>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Having unison of sound, as the octave in music. See
<er>Unison</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 2.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Having always the same drift or tenor; uniform;
certain; regular.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Sir T.
Browne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Unequivocal; indubitable.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Jer. Taylor.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Univocal</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Univocal
<hw>U*niv"o*cal</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Aristotelian
Logic)</fld> <def>A generic term, or a term applicable in the same sense
to all the species it embraces.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A word having but one meaning.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Univocally</ent>⟦br⟧
